s.text: It wins credit for downplaying special effects in favor of story and "exploring the salutary effects of imminent doom" (Janet Maslin, the New York Times ). But it's said to be otherwise soporific, with too few action scenes and characters who seem oddly cavalier about their impending death.
Chernow, who had unprecedented access to Rockefeller's papers, wins praise from the New York Times Book Review for bringing an unusually fine "moral intelligence" to the declining art of biography.
His tale is said to transcend the simplistic views of the mogul as either Horatio Alger success story or venal monopolist.
